        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1963-03-11T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1963-03-11T11:00:00-05:00" n="630"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d630">
                <head>630. Telegram 2241 from Moscow, March 11<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d630fn1">Report on conversation between Trevelyan and <persName
                            corresp="#p_KNS_1">Khrushchev</persName> concerning concessions Soviets
                        made to the United States in Cuba. Secret. 1 p. <gloss target="#t_DOS_1"
                            >DOS</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_CF_1">CF</gloss>, POL 17–1 UK–<gloss
                            target="#t_USSR_1">USSR</gloss>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Moscow</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1963-03-11T19:00:00+03:00">March 11, 1963, 7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <pb facs="d630-1" n="1" type="facsimile" xml:id="d630-1"/>
                <p>Embtel 2234. <persName corresp="#p_KNS_1">Khrushchev</persName>-Trevelyan talk
                    March 6.</p>
                <p>Cuba. <persName corresp="#p_KNS_1">Khrushchev</persName> opened on Cuba by
                    referring to criticisms directed at him for concessions he had made on Cuba. He
                    said it was true that he had made concessions whereas President <persName
                        corresp="#p_KJF_1">Kennedy</persName> had not. When Trevelyan demurred at
                    this, <persName corresp="#p_KNS_1">Khrushchev</persName> replied they were now
                    saying in US that <persName corresp="#p_KJF_1">Kennedy</persName> had not
                    undertaken any commitments with respect to Cuba. <persName corresp="#p_KNS_1"
                        >Khrushchev</persName> said this was “very dangerous and could have fatal
                    consequences”. This might kill the embryo of confidence in a statesman’s world.
                    Trevelyan said he had had impression that liquidation of Cuban affair had
                    established some renewed confidence. <persName corresp="#p_KNS_1"
                        >Khrushchev</persName> replied he had thought so too but now SOVs had to
                    reconsider a little.</p>
                <p>Sir Humphrey said he had impression with respect to Cuba that <persName
                        corresp="#p_KNS_1">Khrushchev</persName> was nervous about finding himself
                    on spot, between US on one side and Chinese Communists on other.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed corresp="#p_KFD_1">
                        <persName corresp="#p_KFD_1">Kohler</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
